      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement in the US roughly spanned the 1950s to the 1980s, evolving through several key stages from peaceful protests and sit-ins to high-profile legislative victories led by figures like MLK and Malcolm X. These efforts successfully dismantled legal segregation under laws like *Brown v. Board of Education* and secured the Voting Rights Act of 1965 to protect Black electoral power. Although significant racial disparities remain today, the movement fundamentally shifted American society toward greater civil rights protections and social justice awareness. Ultimately, it transformed the nation's legal framework and cultural landscape, though ongoing work is needed to fully address systemic inequities.",
